			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">It's not a buffer overflow type of problem clientside, the disconnect is initiated from the server(serverside right after it sends that amount to a client, thus the problem cannot be fixed clientside by simply ignoring it or avoiding it.
<br />

<br />
The server simply assumes that a client recieving that much data at once has crashed/malfunctioned and thus it disconnects it wether or not the client could have handled it or not.
<br />

<br />
It must be fixed serverside by uppening the trigger or assumption of by simply removing it all together.</span><span class="gensmall"><br /><br />Last edited by Amona on Sun Jan 30, 2005 10:01 pm; edited 1 time in total</span></td>
			</tr>
