				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>shadowgod wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Kir wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
There are two problems. This one can be relativly fixed like you proposed.
<br />
But fixing OUR bots will not prevent the flaw of the bad usage of a custom made bot. The hole has to be closed server-side. Cause in the recieving way, this is the server that disconnects you. This is not your aochat class that malfunctions.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
then i think if its bad enough, it should then be considered an exploit, and thusly genevra (however spelt) would be the one to contact, not the community rep... silliorn &lt;sp&gt;.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Everyone at FC has been contacted about it atleast a couple of times, last time I tested it with Jesper on all the dimensions live and on test, and he said straight out what the exact problem was, it's got to do with the caching of incoming packets on the server, and how they are sent back out, the problem is the cache can't time the incoming packets and cache too much/too many, as it would quickly produce a lag problem serverside or simply a situation where too much data were in queqe on the server. Yes it is an exploit, and it's always been there and Jesper said back then (7-8 months ago) it would be fixed, but not over night as it required some restructuring of how the server handles all packets.
<br />

<br />
The same exploit allows for 1 single client to crash everyone witnessing the data ex. in a guildchannel, disconnecting everyone. Meaning it's not just a 1on1 exploit, but a 1on-whole-groupchats exploit.
<br />

<br />
Potencially, someone could send out a overflow like that into one of the public dimensionwide channels, and crash everyone who has that channel on. There are also atleast 2 known special character-combinations that will do the same, that will actually crash the AO client, not just disconnecting it, but cause AO's client to crash and sometimes Windows XP itself to go BSOD. I sent the exact details about it to FC back then too, but didn't get any reply on it. I sent the info twice, and still i got no comment on it.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
